TY  - JOUR
T1  - Foreign Investments of U.S. Individual Investors: Causes and Consequences
AU  - Bailey, Warren
AU  - Kumar, Alok
AU  - Ng, David
Y1  - 2008/03/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0793
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0793
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 443
EP  - 459
VL  - 54
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Using thousands of brokerage accounts of U.S. individual investors, we analyze the motivations and consequences of foreign equity investment. We find that diversification is not the only reason that investors trade foreign securities. While wealthier, more experienced investors enjoy an informational advantage and, thus, are more likely to invest overseas and experience good portfolio performance, other investors appear to venture abroad for the wrong reasons. In particular, behaviorally biased investors often underuse or misuse foreign equity securities and experience poor portfolio performance. Some investors appear to use foreign securities for speculation or to improve upon poor domestic portfolio performance.
AB  - Using thousands of brokerage accounts of U.S. individual investors, we analyze the motivations and consequences of foreign equity investment. We find that diversification is not the only reason that investors trade foreign securities. While wealthier, more experienced investors enjoy an informational advantage and, thus, are more likely to invest overseas and experience good portfolio performance, other investors appear to venture abroad for the wrong reasons. In particular, behaviorally biased investors often underuse or misuse foreign equity securities and experience poor portfolio performance. Some investors appear to use foreign securities for speculation or to improve upon poor domestic portfolio performance.
